04886nam a22007335i 9780813569550DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014021723  a97808135695507 a10.36019/97808135695502doi  a(DE-B1597)529619  a(OCoLC)910662932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aJK1759b.A58 2015 4aJK1759 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a323.6/2309732231 aAptekar, Sofya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Road to Citizenship :bWhat Naturalization Means for Immigrants and the United States /cSofya Aptekar. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (190 p.) :b8 figures, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Roads to Citizenship -- t2. Citizenship and Inequality -- t3. Voices of Immigrants -- t4. Citizenship Ceremonies -- t5. Welcoming and Defining -- t6. Naturalization in Theory and Practice -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 2000 and 2011, eight million immigrants became American citizens. In naturalization ceremonies large and small these new Americans pledged an oath of allegiance to the United States, gaining the right to vote, serve on juries, and hold political office; access to certain jobs; and the legal rights of full citizens. In The Road to Citizenship, Sofya Aptekar analyzes what the process of becoming a citizen means for these newly minted Americans and what it means for the United States as a whole. Examining the evolution of the discursive role of immigrants in American society from potential traitors to morally superior “supercitizens,” Aptekar’s in-depth research uncovers considerable contradictions with the way naturalization works today. Census data reveal that citizenship is distributed in ways that increasingly exacerbate existing class and racial inequalities, at the same time that immigrants’ own understandings of naturalization defy accepted stories we tell about assimilation, citizenship, and becoming American. Aptekar contends that debates about immigration must be broadened beyond the current focus on borders and documentation to include larger questions about the definition of citizenship. Aptekar’s work brings into sharp relief key questions about the overall system: does the current naturalization process accurately reflect our priorities as a nation and reflect the values we wish to instill in new residents and citizens? Should barriers to full membership in the American polity be lowered? What are the implications of keeping the process the same or changing it? Using archival research, interviews, analysis of census and survey data, and participant observation of citizenship ceremonies, The Road to Citizenship demonstrates the ways in which naturalization itself reflects the larger operations of social cohesion and democracy in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited States. 0aNaturalizationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anaturalization practices and laws.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356955040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813569550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813569550.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA